###  https://www.w3id.org/climoo#ClimOO_0000163
:ClimOO_0000163 rdf:type owl:Class ;
                owl:equivalentClass _:genid1356 ;
                rdfs:subClassOf :ClimOO_0000150 ,
                                _:genid1378 ;
                <http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasBroadSynonym> "synthetic polymer debris"@en ;
                <http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasExactSynonym> "plastic debris, plastic litter"@en ;
                rdfs:comment "Classification systems for plastic debris vary, especially according to particle size. For instance, EnvO considers 5 mm as the upper-level threshold to define microplastic particles, as this is a commonly recognized size edge in discussions on microplastic litter. Nevertheless, this is merely an operative definition, and there is no complete consensus on employing it (Hartmann et al., 2019). Hartmann et al. (2019) propose a range of 1-1000 micrometers. The ClimOO ontology includes EnvO classification of plastic debris particles and complements and maps it with that proposed by Hartmann et al. (2019). These classifications differentiate for the size range of micro-, macro-, and meso-plastic particles. The shared size ranges for mega- and nano-plastic particles. This is also intended to be an initial guideline to align and map different classification systems."@en ,
                             "From a material science perspective (which is the one we have to refer to for classifying plastics and polymers) plastic materials are constituted by polymers that are thermosetting and thermoplastic, and not, for instance, by elastic polymers. There exist, however, some synthetic combinations, such as thermoplastic elastomer-based synthetic materials, that are composed by polymers presenting both elastic and plastic properties. Strictly speaking, the last are not plastics (material science perspective). However, these materials are included in the count of debris (from an environmental perspective which is the one we have to refer to for classifying debris and pollution). So, the ClimOO Ontology accounts for these two perspectives, modeling differences and interconnection."@en ;
                rdfs:label "plastic debris particle"@en ;
                <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A piece of polymer-based synthetic material that, at a certain time, is 1) solid, 2) not soluble in water, 3) persistent in environment (bearing a disposition to environmental persistence), generally as pollutant, according to some stakeholder perspective, 4) mobile, 5) does not bear function(s) that can be realized in the some process of usage of some piece of synthetic polymer-based material, and 6) are part of some environmental material as a result of a plastic pollution process."@en ;
                <https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/meta/AnnotationVocabulary/maturity> <https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/core/meta/AnnotationVocabulary/Released> ;
                <https://www.w3id.org/sco#SCO_0000039> :ClimOO_0000072 ,
                                                       :ClimOO_0000073 ,
                                                       :ClimOO_0000074 ,
                                                       :ClimOO_0000075 ,
                                                       :ClimOO_0000228 .

